      "role": "user",
      "content": "yo, i'm stuck on this problem for a contest. the constraints are super tight (256MB memory, 1.0s time) and every time i try a standard DP approach with a large 2D array it hits MLE. i think the state space is just too big for a normal matrix.\n\nhere's the problem: \nGiven an N x N grid where N up to 50,000, and M queries of range sums. The grid is sparse but the number of queries is huge. I need to compute sum(r1, c1, r2, c2) for each query. \n\nmy current code:\n```python\nimport sys\n\ndef solve():\n    # simulated large grid approach\n    N = 50000\n    grid = [[0] * N for _ in range(N)] # obviously this causes MLE\n    \n    # ... rest of logic\n```\n\ni can't fit the grid. can u help me write a python solution that passes the memory limit and the 1s time limit? i dont care how you do it, just need it to not crash the judge.",
